    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-01-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-01-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="361"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.623 Coal/16</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        German Ambassador (<persName type="to">Von Prittwitz</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-17">January 17,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to refer to previous
                    correspondence with you in regard to certain provisions of the Revenue Act of
                    1932, affecting the importation of coal into the United States.</p>
                <p>I now have to inform you that the Decision of the Treasury Department<note n="53"
                        xml:id="d361fn53">Decision No. 45991–6, November 14, 1932; for text, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Treasury Decisions</hi>, vol. 62, p. 521.</note>
                    permitting duty free entry of German coal has, by reason of a ruling of the
                    Attorney General, been reversed. Two copies each of the Attorney General’s
                    letter of December 27, 1932, to the President,<note n="54" xml:id="d361fn54">37
                        Op. Atty. Gen. 34.</note> and of a Decision dated January 9, 1933,<note
                        n="55" xml:id="d361fn55">No. 46102; <hi rend="italic">Treasury
                            Decisions</hi>, vol. 63, pp. 67–68.</note> by the Secretary of the
                    Treasury, are enclosed herewith for your information.</p>
                <p>You will note that the Attorney General has set aside the Decision of the
                    Treasury Department in order that the question of the right of German coal to
                    exemption from the tax imposed by the Revenue Act may be decided by the
                    appropriate court on appeal thereto by the parties interested.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. L. Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
